{"title_page": "Patrick Queen", "text_new": "{{short description|American football middle linebacker}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n| name            = Patrick Queen\n| image           = Patrick Queen LSU2019.jpg\n| image_size      = 250px\n| caption         =Queen at LSU in 2019\n| school          = LSU Tigers\n| currentnumber   = 8\n| currentposition = [[Middle linebacker]]\n| class           = Junior\n| pastschools     = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] (2017\u20132019)\n| bowlgames       = \n*[[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)]]\n*[[2019 Peach Bowl]]\n*[[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]]\n| highschool      = [[Livonia High School (Louisiana)|Livonia High School]]\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1999|8|13}}\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 1\n| weight_lb       = 227\n| highlights      = \n*[[College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP National Champion]] ([[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2019]])\n|espn=4242207\n}}\n'''Patrick Queen''' is an American [[college football]] [[middle linebacker]] for the [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nQueen grew up in [[Ventress, Louisiana]] and attended [[Livonia High School (Louisiana)|Livonia High School]], where he played both linebacker and running back.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_6d330be4-daf4-11e9-9156-17a9adfadaa7.html|title=Patrick Queen is the 'miracle baby' dedicated to LSU from birth; 'One of our best players'|last=Kubena|first=Brooks|date=September 20, 2019|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> As a senior, he rushed for 1,487 yards and 19 touchdowns on offense and had 66 tackles, seven tackles for losses, and six passes broken up on defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wafb.com/2020/01/13/eye-title-patrick-queen-parents-coaches-reflect-lsu-lbs-legendary-career-livonia-high-school/|title=EYE ON THE TITLE: Patrick Queen, parents, and coaches reflect on LSU LB\u2019s legendary career at Livonia High School|last=Doucet|first=Jacques|date=January 13, 2020|website=[[WAFB]]|publisher=[[Gray Television]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n[[File:2020-0113-OrgeronBurrowQueen.PNG|thumb|left|200px|Queen at the post-game presser for the 2020 National Championship game where he was named Defensive MVP.]]\nQueen made six tackles in 12 games played as a true freshman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_b0830fa8-d716-11e8-a4e1-37c6795bf4db.html|title=LSU's Patrick Queen tops rotation in Devin White's place; Garrett Brumfield works out; other practice notes|last=Rabalais|first=Scott|date=October 23, 2018|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> He finished his sophomore season with 40 tackles, 5.0 tackles for loss and a sack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theathletic.com/1377511/2019/11/14/lsu-football-linebacker-patrick-queen-patience-ole-miss/|title=\u2018I\u2019ve never met anybody who wants it more than he does\u2019: Appreciating the patience of Patrick Queen|last=Miller|first=Brody|date=November 14, 2019|website=[[The Athletic]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Queen entered his junior year on the watchlist for the Butkus Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wafb.com/2019/07/22/lsu-leads-nation-with-linebackers-named-butkus-award-watch-list/|title=LSU leads nation with 4 linebackers named to Butkus Award Watch List|last=Auzenne|first=Josh|date=July 22, 2019|website=[[WAFB]]|publisher=[[Gray Television]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Queen finished the regular season with 69 tackles (eight for a loss), 2.5 sacks, three pass deflections, two breakups, an interception and a fumble recovery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/oklahoma/Article/Patrick-Queen-bulletin-board-material-LSU-Tigers-College-Football-Playoff-141095375/|title=LSU\u2019s Queen: OU O-line, backs not great, \"going to dominate\"|last=Helmer|first=Joey|date=December 26, 2019|website=[[247Sports.com]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> Queen was named the Defensive MVP of the [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]] after making eight tackles with 2.5 for a loss and a combined sack against Clemson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_447132ee-367f-11ea-af81-335a5a48c669.html|title=Patrick Queen-led defense helps LSU fend off Clemson|last=Just|first=Amie|date=January 13, 2020|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Following the end of the season Queen announced that he would forgo his senior season to enter the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/lsu/Article/LSU-Football-Patrick-Queen-NFL-Draft-2020-decision-142245053/|title=Patrick Queen declares for 2020 NFL Draft|last=Embody|first=Billy|date=January 15, 2020|website=[[247Sports.com]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://lsusports.net/sports/football/roster/patrick-queen/20292 LSU Tigers bio]\n\n{{2019 LSU Tigers football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chaisson, KLavon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:People from Pointe Coupee Parish, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football middle linebacker}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{Infobox college football player\n| name            = Patrick Queen\n| image           = Patrick Queen LSU2019.jpg\n| image_size      = 250px\n| caption         =Queen at LSU in 2019\n| school          = LSU Tigers\n| currentnumber   = 8\n| currentposition = [[Middle linebacker]]\n| class           = Junior\n| pastschools     = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] (2017\u20132019)\n| bowlgames       = \n*[[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)]]\n*[[2019 Peach Bowl]]\n*[[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]]\n| highschool      = [[Livonia High School (Louisiana)|Livonia High School]]\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1999|8|13}}\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 1\n| weight_lb       = 227\n| highlights      = \n*[[College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP National Champion]] ([[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2019]])\n|espn=4242207\n}}\n'''Patrick Queen''' is an American [[college football]] [[middle linebacker]] for the [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nQueen grew up in [[Ventress, Louisiana]] and attended [[Livonia High School (Louisiana)|Livonia High School]], where he played both linebacker and running back.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_6d330be4-daf4-11e9-9156-17a9adfadaa7.html|title=Patrick Queen is the 'miracle baby' dedicated to LSU from birth; 'One of our best players'|last=Kubena|first=Brooks|date=September 20, 2019|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> As a senior, he rushed for 1,487 yards and 19 touchdowns on offense and had 66 tackles, seven tackles for losses, and six passes broken up on defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wafb.com/2020/01/13/eye-title-patrick-queen-parents-coaches-reflect-lsu-lbs-legendary-career-livonia-high-school/|title=EYE ON THE TITLE: Patrick Queen, parents, and coaches reflect on LSU LB\u2019s legendary career at Livonia High School|last=Doucet|first=Jacques|date=January 13, 2020|website=[[WAFB]]|publisher=[[Gray Television]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n[[File:2020-0113-OrgeronBurrowQueen.PNG|thumb|left|200px|Queen at the post-game presser for the 2020 National Championship game where he was named Defensive MVP.]]\nQueen made six tackles in 12 games played as a true freshman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_b0830fa8-d716-11e8-a4e1-37c6795bf4db.html|title=LSU's Patrick Queen tops rotation in Devin White's place; Garrett Brumfield works out; other practice notes|last=Rabalais|first=Scott|date=October 23, 2018|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> He finished his sophomore season with 40 tackles, 5.0 tackles for loss and a sack.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theathletic.com/1377511/2019/11/14/lsu-football-linebacker-patrick-queen-patience-ole-miss/|title=\u2018I\u2019ve never met anybody who wants it more than he does\u2019: Appreciating the patience of Patrick Queen|last=Miller|first=Brody|date=November 14, 2019|website=[[The Athletic]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Queen entered his junior year on the watchlist for the Butkus Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wafb.com/2019/07/22/lsu-leads-nation-with-linebackers-named-butkus-award-watch-list/|title=LSU leads nation with 4 linebackers named to Butkus Award Watch List|last=Auzenne|first=Josh|date=July 22, 2019|website=[[WAFB]]|publisher=[[Gray Television]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Queen finished the regular season with 69 tackles (eight for a loss), 2.5 sacks, three pass deflections, two breakups, an interception and a fumble recovery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/oklahoma/Article/Patrick-Queen-bulletin-board-material-LSU-Tigers-College-Football-Playoff-141095375/|title=LSU\u2019s Queen: OU O-line, backs not great, \"going to dominate\"|last=Helmer|first=Joey|date=December 26, 2019|website=[[247Sports.com]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> Queen was named the Defensive MVP of the [[2020 College Football Playoff National Championship|2020 National Championship Game]] after making eight tackles with 2.5 for a loss and a combined sack against Clemson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_447132ee-367f-11ea-af81-335a5a48c669.html|title=Patrick Queen-led defense helps LSU fend off Clemson|last=Just|first=Amie|date=January 13, 2020|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Following the end of the season Queen announced that he would forgo his senior season to enter the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/lsu/Article/LSU-Football-Patrick-Queen-NFL-Draft-2020-decision-142245053/|title=Patrick Queen declares for 2020 NFL Draft|last=Embody|first=Billy|date=January 15, 2020|website=[[247Sports.com]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://lsusports.net/sports/football/roster/patrick-queen/20292 LSU Tigers bio]\n\n{{2019 LSU Tigers football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chaisson, K'Lavon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:People from Pointe Coupee Parish, Louisiana]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Queen"}
{"title_page": "Nathaniel Erskine-Smith", "text_new": "{{Infobox CanadianMP\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Nathaniel Erskine-Smith\n| honorific-suffix ={{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP|size=100%}}\n| image            = Nathaniel Erskine-Smith at the East York Canada Day Parade - 2018 (42256213615) (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Erskine-Smith at a Canada Day Parade in 2018\n| riding           = [[Beaches\u2014East York]]\n| parliament       = Canadian\n| term_start       = October 19, 2015\n| term_end         =\n| predecessor      = [[Matthew Kellway]]\n| successor        =\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| residence        = [[The Beaches|The Beaches, Toronto]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.insidetoronto.com/news-story/6213526-rookie-mps-julie-dabrusin-and-nathaniel-erskine-smith-eager-to-get-to-work-in-2016/ | title=Rookie MPs Julie Dabrusin and Nathaniel Erskine-Smith eager to get to work in 2016 | publisher=[[Metroland Media]] | work=[[Inside Toronto]] | date=January 2, 2016 | accessdate=October 2, 2016 | author=Lavoie, Joanna}}</ref><ref name=\"Six questions\" />\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1984|06|15}}\n| birth_place      = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| profession       = Lawyer\n| alma_mater       = {{ubl | [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] | [[University of Oxford]]}}\n| spouse           = Amy Symington\n|}}\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\n'''Nathaniel Erskine-Smith''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} was born in Toronto, Ontario, on June 15, 1984. His parents Sara Erskine and Lawrence Smith were public school teachers. He obtained a B.A. (Politics)  and a J.D. (Law) in 2010 from [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen\u2019s University at Kingston]]. When he was a student at Queen's, he was an unsuccessful candidate for city council for Sydenham District in [[Kingston, Ontario]], in the [[2006 Ontario municipal elections#Kingston|2006 municipal elections]]. Erskine-Smith studied [[political philosophy]] and constitutional law at the [[University of Oxford]] where he earned a [[Master of Laws]] ([[Bachelor of Civil Law|BCL]]) degree <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nerskine-smith.liberal.ca/biography/|title=Biography {{!}} Nathaniel Erskine-Smith {{!}} Your member of parliament for Beaches-East York|website=nerskine-smith.liberal.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Before Politics ==\n\n=== Legal Career ===\nNathaniel practised commercial litigation as an associate at Kramer Simaan Dhillon, after working as a law student at Aird & Berlis LLP. He also performed volunteer work for the Canadian Civil Liberties Association. He worked pro bono for a range of clients and causes, including a civil liberties case to protect religious freedom in Ontario\u2019s school system. In that noteworthy pro bono civil liberties case in 2014, Nathaniel successfully argued against compulsory religious studies at publicly funded high schools in Ontario.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/holy-post/father-wins-right-to-have-son-exempted-from-all-religious-programs-at-ontario-catholic-high-school|title=Father wins right to have son exempted from all religious programs at Ontario Catholic high school {{!}} National Post|last=Post|first=Holy|date=2014-04-08|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Election Results==\nIn the 2015 federal election Nathaniel \u201cNate\u201d Erskine-Smith was the winning Liberal candidate in the riding of Beaches-East York. He defeated New Democrat incumbent Matthew Kellway by 10,345 votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/2284103/nathaniel-erskine-smith-reclaims-beaches-east-york-for-liberals/|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith reclaims Beaches-East York for Liberals|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Erskine-Smith became the youngest MP elected from the Greater Toronto Area<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/09/09/beacheseast-york-mp-is-a-different-political-animal-delacourt.html|title=Beaches\u2014East York MP is a different political animal: Delacourt|date=2016-09-09|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In the 2019 federal election Erskine-Smith was re-elected with 32,647 total votes, which was the all-time largest margin of victory of 20,204 votes and the all-time largest share of the vote (57.2%) in Beaches-East York\u2019s history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e|title=Election Night Results - Electoral Districts|last=Canada|first=Elections|website=enr.elections.ca|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Legislation & Parliament ==\n\n=== Last Parliament (42nd Parliament, 2015-2019) ===\n\n==== Committee Work ====\nErskine-Smith served as a member of the Public Safety and National Security Committee, and as the Vice-Chair of the Access to Information, Privacy and Ethics committee in the 42nd parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lop.parl.ca/sites/ParlInfo/default/en_CA/|title=Home|website=lop.parl.ca|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Other Roles ====\nHe served as the president of the Canadian group of the Inter-Parliamentary Union for a one-year term in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toronto.com/news-story/6374744-beaches-east-york-mp-nathaniel-erskine-smith-represents-canada-on-the-inter-parliamentary-union/|title=Beaches-East York MP Nathaniel Erskine-Smith represents Canada on the Inter-Parliamentary Union|date=2016-03-03|website=Toronto.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In that capacity, he delivered a speech about youth in politics at an IPU meeting in Zambia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/09/09/beacheseast-york-mp-is-a-different-political-animal-delacourt.html|title=Beaches\u2014East York MP is a different political animal: Delacourt|date=2016-09-09|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Independence ====\nErskine-Smith has been called Canada\u2019s most independent parliamentarian, having set records for voting against his own party. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/wherry-erskinesmith-dissent-rebel-1.3639881|title=The least predictable MP highlights a slightly unpredictable Parliament|last=Wherry|first=Aaron|date=June 17, 2016|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> The Toronto Star has described him as \u201ca breath of fresh air,\u201d The National Post has called him a \u201cmaverick,\u201d and the CBC referred to him as Ottawa\u2019s \u201cleast predictable MP.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/politics/political-opinion/2019/03/26/nathaniel-erskine-smith-provides-a-rare-breath-of-fresh-air-in-the-snc-lavalin-affair.html|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith provides a rare breath of fresh air in the SNC-Lavalin affair|date=2019-03-26|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and Ottawa\u2019s \u201cleast predictable MP.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe has voted against party lines when arguing for better assisted dying laws, declaring ISIS guilty of genocide, expunging cannabis possession records, ending public fossil fuel subsidies, among other issues, and he maintains a public record to explain each dissenting vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nerskine-smith.liberal.ca/page/independence/|title=Principled Independence {{!}} Nathaniel Erskine-Smith {{!}} Your member of parliament for Beaches-East York|website=nerskine-smith.liberal.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nErskine-Smith has written and spoken about the need for greater independence in Parliament, and to highlight the importance of thoughtful and respectful disagreement. For example, in an op-ed in The Toronto Star, he wrote:\n\n\u201cNo political party represents our views perfectly. We find the party that best represents our views and values, and we engage, debate and organize to bring both our party and country closer to those objectives. I am a Liberal MP and I continue to support our Liberal government. But that does not mean that I support every government action taken, or that I ought to refrain from public disagreement. In contrast to blind partisan loyalty, we promised to empower MPs and their communities through more free votes in the House of Commons.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nerskine-smith.liberal.ca/page/independence/|title=Principled Independence {{!}} Nathaniel Erskine-Smith {{!}} Your member of parliament for Beaches-East York|website=nerskine-smith.liberal.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Animal Welfare and Bill C-246 ====\nIn 2015, Erskine-Smith seconded Bill S-203, the Ending the Captivity of Whales and Dolphins Act, that became law in June 2019. The bill prohibits the captivity of cetaceans and requires permits to import and export them to and from Canada. Erskine-Smith spoke to the house about the importance of the bill in June 2018.<ref>{{Citation|title=Protecting Endangered Whales|url=https://www.facebook.com/beynate/videos/protecting-endangered-whales/1753037771482075/|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://openparliament.ca/debates/2018/6/4/nathaniel-erskine-smith-1/|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith, \"Endangered Whales\" on June 4th, 2018 {{!}} openparliament.ca|website=openparliament.ca|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nOn February 26, 2016, Erskine-Smith introduced Bill C-246, the Modernizing Animal Protections Act,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/10/06/nathaniel-erskine-smith-animal-cruelty-bill-c-246_n_12371614.html|title=Liberal MP's Animal Cruelty Bill Defeated|date=2016-10-06|website=HuffPost Canada|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> to ban the import of shark fins and make Canada's animal cruelty laws tougher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/09/09/beacheseast-york-mp-is-a-different-political-animal-delacourt.html|title=Beaches\u2014East York MP is a different political animal: Delacourt|date=2016-09-09|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The bill won support from EndCruelty, a coalition of Canadians who support stronger animal protection laws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://endcruelty.ca/|title=End Animal Cruelty \u2013 Support Bill C-246|website=EndCruelty.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Due to concerns from animal use lobbyists, the bill was defeated 198 to 84 at second reading. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/10/06/nathaniel-erskine-smith-animal-cruelty-bill-c-246_n_12371614.html|title=Liberal MP's Animal Cruelty Bill Defeated|date=2016-10-06|website=HuffPost Canada|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Two years later, a government bill addressing similar concerns was tabled by Justice Minister Jody Wilson-Raybould. She acknowledged Erskine-Smith\u2019s efforts as a precursor to the government\u2019s legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/politics/feds-to-ban-all-forms-of-bestiality-crack-down-on-animal-fighting-1.4139552|title=Feds to ban all forms of bestiality, crack down on animal fighting|date=2018-10-18|website=CTVNews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The defeat of Erskine-Smith\u2019s Bill C-246 led to the creation of the Liberal Animal Welfare Caucus in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2017/02/01/liberal-internal-caucus-to-focus-on-animal-welfare/|title=Liberal internal caucus to focus on animal welfare|last=Feb 1|first=Kelsey Johnson Published on|last2=2017 11:42am|date=2017-02-01|website=iPolitics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> On September 5, 2017, Erskine-Smith wrote a piece in Now Magazine addressing his veganism and the importance of a social change towards the treatment of animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/api/content/95e50ec6-927a-11e7-b25f-121bebc5777e/|title=Opinion: Why I\u2019m a vegan but don\u2019t consider myself an animal activist|last=Erskine-Smith|first=Nathaniel|date=2017-09-05|website=NOW Magazine|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n====== Animal Welfare Awards ======\nIn 2016, Erskine-Smith received the Humane Legislator Award from Animal Justice for his efforts to modernize Canada\u2019s federal animal protection laws with Bill C-246.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animaljustice.ca/blog/2016-pro-bono-humane-legislator-awards-recognize-outstanding-advocacy|title=2016 Pro Bono & Humane Legislator Awards Recognize Outstanding Advocates|date=2016-12-29|website=Animal Justice|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In 2017, Erskine-Smith received the Fur-Bearers\u2019 Clements award for his dedication to improving the lives of animals with Bill C-246.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/FURfree/posts/10154857911851269|title=The Fur-Bearers|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefurbearers.com/blog/episode-401-nathaniels-message-hope|title=EPISODE 401: NATHANIEL'S MESSAGE OF HOPE|last=|first=|date=2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2019, Erskine-Smith was awarded the Toronto Vegetarian Association Lisa Grill Compassion for Animals Award for his compassion and commitment toward animals. He was also recognized by Humane Canada for his dedication to ending animal abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/beynate/posts/2606045602847950|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/beynate/posts/2563478323771345|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Climate Action and Bill C-454 ====\nIn October 2018, Erskine-Smith called an emergency debate on climate change in Parliament in response to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change\u2019s special report on global warming. He requested action to be taken by the government and Canadians to ensure that Canada can reduce its emissions and reach the targeted goals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/10/16/trudeau-government-urged-to-step-up-climate-action-in-emergency-debate_a_23562480/|title=Trudeau Government Urged To Step Up Climate Action In Emergency Debate|date=2018-10-16|website=HuffPost Canada|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> On June 5, 2019, Erskine-Smith introduced Bill C-454, the Net-Zero Greenhouse Gas Emissions Act, to require the Government of Canada to reduce GHG emissions to net zero by 2050.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parl.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/bill/C-454/first-reading|title=Private Member's Bill C-454 (42-1) - First Reading - Net-Zero Greenhouse Gas Emissions Act - Parliament of Canada|website=www.parl.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/politics/federal/2019/06/05/liberal-mp-proposes-net-zero-emissions-target-for-2050.html|title=Liberal MP proposes \u2018net zero\u2019 emissions target for 2050|date=2019-06-05|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==== Drug Policy Reform and Bill C-460 ====\nErskine-Smith believes that the war on drugs has been a failure. He has been a vocal supporter of cannabis legalization and regulation, and has called for a new approach to treat drug use as a health issue. In February 2016, Erskine-Smith represented the Canadian government's pro-marijuana legalization views to a joint United Nations/Inter-Parliamentary Union conference reviewing how different countries were dealing with illegal drugs. He partnered with Mexican Senator Laura Rojas to argue that countries should seek alternatives to incarceration in cases where individuals have drugs solely for personal use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2016/02/08/liberal-mp-brings-governments-pro-pot-stance-to-world-stage/|title=Liberal MP brings government's pro-pot stance to world stage|last=Feb 8|first=Kyle Duggan Published on|last2=2016 5:00am|date=2016-02-08|website=iPolitics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In early January 2017, Erskine-Smith published an op-ed in Vice News Canada calling for the decriminalization of all drug possession as a logical next step to the government\u2019s progressive drug policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/3kpgw9/im-a-member-of-trudeaus-liberals-and-i-think-the-government-should-decriminalize-all-drugs|title=I'm a member of Trudeau's Liberals and I think the government should decriminalize all drugs|last=Erskine-Smith|first=Nathaniel|date=2017-01-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In late January 2017, Erskine-Smith delivered a speech in the House of Commons in support of Bill C-37, to expand access to safe injection clinics across Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcommons.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/house/sitting-130/hansard#Int-9331689|title=Debates (Hansard) No. 130 - January 31, 2017 (42-1) - House of Commons of Canada|website=www.ourcommons.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In the first episode of the television series Political Blind Date in 2017, Erskine-Smith and Conservative MP Garnett Genuis discussed their differing perspectives on the legalization of marijuana in Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2017/11/04/political-blind-date-series-hopes-opposites-attract-or-at-least-get-along.html|title=Political Blind Date series hopes opposites attract, or at least get along|date=2017-11-04|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Erskine-Smith introduced a Liberal caucus policy resolution to address the opioid crisis through a public health approach, and it was adopted as the second overall priority by the grassroots Liberal membership at the Liberal Policy Convention in Halifax in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/sex-work-drugs-and-pharmacare-what-liberals-want-in-2019-platform-1.3892062|title=Sex work, drugs and pharmacare: What Liberals want in 2019 platform|date=2018-04-21|website=CTVNews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Bill C-460 ====\nTo ensure more people access treatment, Nate introduced a bill to remove criminal sanctions for low-level possession and to reduce the stigma associated with seeking treatment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/decriminalization-drugs-canada_ca_5d0f8751e4b0aa375f4e1b8c|title=Why A Liberal MP Tabled A Bill To Decriminalize Hard Drugs At The Worst Time|date=2019-06-23|website=HuffPost Canada|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In 2018, Erskine-Smith appeared on CBC\u2019s Power & Politics to speak about his disappointment in the Liberal government\u2019s signing of the United States\u2019 \u2018War on Drugs\u2019 document. He argued it brought the conversation about drugs away from a health issue, which ran counter to his push for drug decriminalization and domestic policy at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/apr/16/canada-liberal-party-considers-decriminalization-all-illicit-drugs|title=Canada's Liberal party considers decriminalization of all illicit drugs|date=2018-04-16|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/player/play/1332258371793|title=Canada endorsed U.S. 'war on drugs' document to appease U.S., Liberal MP says|last=|first=|date=2018|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Cannabis Record Expungement ====\nErskine-Smith seconded a bill introduced by NDP MP Murray Rankin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/liberals-urged-to-follow-u-s-jurisdictions-to-expunge-cannabis-records-1.4337743|title=Liberals urged to follow U.S. jurisdictions to expunge cannabis records|last=Kirkup|first=Kristy|date=2019-03-15|website=CTVNews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In March 2019, Erskine-Smith wrote an op-ed for NOW Magazine where he discussed his support for MP Rankin\u2019s bill, stating that only expungements would address the injustice of cannabis criminalization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/api/content/9cc61654-41dd-11e9-b0fa-120e7ad5cf50/|title=Pot pardons don't go far enough to address racial injustices, says Liberal MP|last=Erskine-Smith|first=Nathaniel|date=2019-03-12|website=NOW Magazine|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Privacy Work ====\nIn 2017, Erskine-Smith traveled to Washington <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/beynate/posts/1465898100196045|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> with the Access to Information, Privacy and Ethics committee to attend a congressional hearing on the Equifax data breach, and met with Congressmen from the Digital Commerce subcommittee, with Facebook<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/facebookappCanada/|title=Facebook app|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> privacy experts, and with officials from the Federal Trade Commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/federaltradecommission/|title=Federal Trade Commission|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In May 2018, Erskine-Smith scrutinized Facebook <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/|title=Facebook - Log In or Sign Up|website=Facebook|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>officials at the Standing Committee on Access to Information, Privacy and Ethics <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcommons.ca/Committees/en/ETHI|title=ETHI - Home - House of Commons of Canada|website=www.ourcommons.ca|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> regarding the Cambridge Analytica scandal and the extent of privacy breaches for Canadians.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-what-is-cambridge-analytica-and-what-did-it-do-a-guide/|title=Cambridge Analytica, AggregateIQ and the Facebook scandal: A guide to who\u2019s accused of what|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In 2018, Erskine-Smith participated as the Canadian delegation in the U.K.\u2019s International Grand Committee on social media and disinformation. In total, 24 officials from 9 countries representing 447 million people participated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://business.financialpost.com/technology/remember-the-internet-of-the-90s-thats-what-our-outdated-privacy-rules-were-built-to-handle|title=Remember the internet of the \u201990s? That\u2019s what Canada\u2019s outdated data protection laws were meant to handle {{!}} Financial Post|last=Innovation|date=2018-12-11|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In June 2018, Erskine-Smith introduced Bill-C413, an Act to amend the Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act, to give new powers for the Privacy Commissioner to better protect our privacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2018/06/20/liberal-backbencher-tables-bill-to-give-privacy-commissioner-more-power/|title=Liberal backbencher tables bill to give privacy commissioner more power|last=Jun 20|first=Sarah Turnbull Published on|last2=2018 4:00pm|date=2018-06-20|website=iPolitics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In May 2019, Erskine-Smith participated in the Canadian delegation of the International Grand Committee <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/facebook-zuckerberg-cambridge-analytica-1.5127007|title=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/facebook-zuckerberg-cambridge-analytica-1.5127007|last=|first=|date=2019|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> to meet with representatives from Google, Facebook and Twitter, among others. The Silicon Valley representatives were asked to defend their companies' records on protecting users' data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/facebook-grand-committee-tuesday-1.5152436|title='Call their bluff': Shut down social media platforms, ex-Facebook adviser urges|last=|first=|date=2019|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In August 2019, Erskine-Smith wrote an op-ed for the Toronto Star expressing his desire for the right to be forgotten. He explained that in an increasingly connected, online world citizens should have the right to hide content published about them from search engines if the individual\u2019s privacy is being seriously violated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/contributors/thebigdebate/2019/08/27/do-people-have-the-right-to-be-forgotten-on-the-internet.html|title=Do people have the right to be forgotten on the internet?|date=2019-08-27|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Current Parliament (43rd Parliament, 2019-Present): ===\n\n==== Committee Work ====\nErskine-Smith is a member of the Standing Committee on Industry, Science and Technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcommons.ca/Committees/en/INDU?parl=42&session=1|title=INDU - Home - House of Commons of Canada|website=www.ourcommons.ca|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==== 2020 Private Members Bills ====\nHe introduced two bills in February 2020.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.beachmetro.com/2020/03/11/beaches-east-york-mp-introduces-private-members-bill-to-emphasize-public-health-over-criminal-charges-in-controlled-drugs-act/|title=Beaches-East York MP introduces Private Members Bill to emphasize public health over criminal charges in controlled drugs act|date=2020-03-11|website=Beach Metro Community News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==== Bill C-235 ====\nThis bill would delete the drug possession offence from the Criminal Code.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Bill C-236 ====\nThis bill would provide diversion options to law enforcement, crown attorneys, and judges for drug possession cases.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nErskine-Smith was raised [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]], and is now [[Veganism|vegan]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/09/09/beacheseast-york-mp-is-a-different-political-animal-delacourt.html|title=Beaches\u2014East York MP is a different political animal: Delacourt|last=Delacourt|first=Susan|date=September 6, 2016|website=thestar.com|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=October 1, 2016}}</ref> He has [[Crohn's disease]].<ref>{{Cite podcast|last=Domise|first=Andray|title=Legal Weed is Bad for Poor People|website=Canadaland Commons|publisher=[[Canadaland]]|date=February 22, 2016|url=http://www.canadalandshow.com/podcast/legal-weed-bad-poor-people-0|access-date=August 30, 2016|time=19:42}}</ref>\n\nErskine-Smith married Amelia \"Amy\" Symington, a prominent Toronto vegan chef and [[nutritionist]], on her family farm in [[Camlachie, Ontario]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The two met in an undergraduate [[film studies]] course at Queen's University.<ref name=\"Kingston\">{{Cite news|last=MacAlpine|first=Ian|url=http://www.thewhig.com/2015/10/26/council-run-helps-fuel-new-mps-success|title=Council run helps fuel new MP\u2019s success|date=October 26, 2015|newspaper=[[Kingston Whig-Standard]]|access-date=August 30, 2016}}</ref> They have two sons together.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.beachmetro.com/2020/01/07/beaches-east-york-mp-nathaniel-erskine-smith-helps-deliver-baby-son-crawford/|title=Beaches-East York MP Nathaniel Erskine-Smith helps deliver baby son Crawford|date=January 7, 2020|work=Beach Metro Community News|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2019|Beaches\u2014East York|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|[[Nathaniel Erskine-Smith]]|32,168|57.2|+7.75|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Mae J. Nam|11,964|21.3|-9.52|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Nadirah Nazeer|7,957|14.2|-2.23|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Sean Manners|3,295|5.9|+3.32|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|PPC|Deborah McKenzie|822|1.5|-|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|56,206|100.0 &nbsp;|| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|80,981}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Liberal|}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>{{cite web |title=List of confirmed candidates |url=https://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/lst&document=index&lang=e |website=Elections Canada |accessdate=4 October 2019}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Election Night Results- |url=https://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e |website=[[Elections Canada]] |accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n{{end}}\n{{Canadian federal election, 2015/Beaches\u2014East York}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Canadian Parliament links|18483}}\n*{{official website|http://nathanielerskinesmith.liberal.ca/}}\n*[https://votenate.ca Campaign Website]\n\n{{Current Members of the Canadian House of Commons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erskine-Smith, Nathaniel}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Queen's University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox CanadianMP\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Nathaniel Erskine-Smith\n| honorific-suffix ={{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP|size=100%}}\n| image            = Nathaniel Erskine-Smith at the East York Canada Day Parade - 2018 (42256213615) (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Erskine-Smith at a Canada Day Parade in 2018\n| riding           = [[Beaches\u2014East York]]\n| parliament       = Canadian\n| term_start       = October 19, 2015\n| term_end         =\n| predecessor      = [[Matthew Kellway]]\n| successor        =\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| residence        = [[The Beaches|The Beaches, Toronto]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.insidetoronto.com/news-story/6213526-rookie-mps-julie-dabrusin-and-nathaniel-erskine-smith-eager-to-get-to-work-in-2016/ | title=Rookie MPs Julie Dabrusin and Nathaniel Erskine-Smith eager to get to work in 2016 | publisher=[[Metroland Media]] | work=[[Inside Toronto]] | date=January 2, 2016 | accessdate=October 2, 2016 | author=Lavoie, Joanna}}</ref><ref name=\"Six questions\" />\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1984|06|15}}\n| birth_place      = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| profession       = Lawyer\n| alma_mater       = {{ubl | [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] | [[University of Oxford]]}}\n| spouse           = Amy Symington\n|}}\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\n'''Nathaniel Erskine-Smith''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} was born in Toronto, Ontario, on June 15, 1984. His parents Sara Erskine and Lawrence Smith were public school teachers. He obtained a B.A. (Politics)  and a J.D. (Law) in 2010 from [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen\u2019s University at Kingston]]. When he was a student at Queen's, he was an unsuccessful candidate for city council for Sydenham District in [[Kingston, Ontario]], in the [[2006 Ontario municipal elections#Kingston|2006 municipal elections]]. Erskine-Smith studied [[political philosophy]] and constitutional law at the [[University of Oxford]] where he earned a [[Master of Laws]] ([[Bachelor of Civil Law|BCL]]) degree\n\n== Before Politics ==\n\n=== Legal Career ===\nNathaniel practised commercial litigation as an associate at Kramer Simaan Dhillon, after working as a law student at Aird & Berlis LLP. He also performed volunteer work for the Canadian Civil Liberties Association. He worked pro bono for a range of clients and causes, including a civil liberties case to protect religious freedom in Ontario\u2019s school system. In that noteworthy pro bono civil liberties case in 2014, Nathaniel successfully argued against compulsory religious studies at publicly funded high schools in Ontario.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/holy-post/father-wins-right-to-have-son-exempted-from-all-religious-programs-at-ontario-catholic-high-school|title=Father wins right to have son exempted from all religious programs at Ontario Catholic high school {{!}} National Post|last=Post|first=Holy|date=2014-04-08|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Election Results==\nIn the 2015 federal election Nathaniel \u201cNate\u201d Erskine-Smith was the winning Liberal candidate in the riding of Beaches-East York. He defeated New Democrat incumbent Matthew Kellway by 10,345 votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/2284103/nathaniel-erskine-smith-reclaims-beaches-east-york-for-liberals/|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith reclaims Beaches-East York for Liberals|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Erskine-Smith became the youngest MP elected from the Greater Toronto Area<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/09/09/beacheseast-york-mp-is-a-different-political-animal-delacourt.html|title=Beaches\u2014East York MP is a different political animal: Delacourt|date=2016-09-09|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In the 2019 federal election Erskine-Smith was re-elected with 32,647 total votes, which was the all-time largest margin of victory of 20,204 votes and the all-time largest share of the vote (57.2%) in Beaches-East York\u2019s history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e|title=Election Night Results - Electoral Districts|last=Canada|first=Elections|website=enr.elections.ca|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Legislation & Parliament ==\n\n=== Last Parliament (42nd Parliament, 2015-2019) ===\n\n==== Committee Work ====\nErskine-Smith served as a member of the Public Safety and National Security Committee, and as the Vice-Chair of the Access to Information, Privacy and Ethics committee in the 42nd parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lop.parl.ca/sites/ParlInfo/default/en_CA/|title=Home|website=lop.parl.ca|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Other Roles ====\nHe served as the president of the Canadian group of the Inter-Parliamentary Union for a one-year term in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toronto.com/news-story/6374744-beaches-east-york-mp-nathaniel-erskine-smith-represents-canada-on-the-inter-parliamentary-union/|title=Beaches-East York MP Nathaniel Erskine-Smith represents Canada on the Inter-Parliamentary Union|date=2016-03-03|website=Toronto.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In that capacity, he delivered a speech about youth in politics at an IPU meeting in Zambia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/09/09/beacheseast-york-mp-is-a-different-political-animal-delacourt.html|title=Beaches\u2014East York MP is a different political animal: Delacourt|date=2016-09-09|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Independence ====\nErskine-Smith has been called Canada\u2019s most independent parliamentarian, having set records for voting against his own party. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/wherry-erskinesmith-dissent-rebel-1.3639881|title=The least predictable MP highlights a slightly unpredictable Parliament|last=Wherry|first=Aaron|date=June 17, 2016|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> The Toronto Star has described him as \u201ca breath of fresh air,\u201d The National Post has called him a \u201cmaverick,\u201d and the CBC referred to him as Ottawa\u2019s \u201cleast predictable MP.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/politics/political-opinion/2019/03/26/nathaniel-erskine-smith-provides-a-rare-breath-of-fresh-air-in-the-snc-lavalin-affair.html|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith provides a rare breath of fresh air in the SNC-Lavalin affair|date=2019-03-26|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and Ottawa\u2019s \u201cleast predictable MP.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe has voted against party lines when arguing for better assisted dying laws, declaring ISIS guilty of genocide, expunging cannabis possession records, ending public fossil fuel subsidies, among other issues, and he maintains a public record to explain each dissenting vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nerskine-smith.liberal.ca/page/independence/|title=Principled Independence {{!}} Nathaniel Erskine-Smith {{!}} Your member of parliament for Beaches-East York|website=nerskine-smith.liberal.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nErskine-Smith has written and spoken about the need for greater independence in Parliament, and to highlight the importance of thoughtful and respectful disagreement. For example, in an op-ed in The Toronto Star, he wrote:\n\n\u201cNo political party represents our views perfectly. We find the party that best represents our views and values, and we engage, debate and organize to bring both our party and country closer to those objectives. I am a Liberal MP and I continue to support our Liberal government. But that does not mean that I support every government action taken, or that I ought to refrain from public disagreement. In contrast to blind partisan loyalty, we promised to empower MPs and their communities through more free votes in the House of Commons.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nerskine-smith.liberal.ca/page/independence/|title=Principled Independence {{!}} Nathaniel Erskine-Smith {{!}} Your member of parliament for Beaches-East York|website=nerskine-smith.liberal.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Animal Welfare and Bill C-246 ====\nIn 2015, Erskine-Smith seconded Bill S-203, the Ending the Captivity of Whales and Dolphins Act, that became law in June 2019. The bill prohibits the captivity of cetaceans and requires permits to import and export them to and from Canada. Erskine-Smith spoke to the house about the importance of the bill in June 2018.<ref>{{Citation|title=Protecting Endangered Whales|url=https://www.facebook.com/beynate/videos/protecting-endangered-whales/1753037771482075/|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://openparliament.ca/debates/2018/6/4/nathaniel-erskine-smith-1/|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith, \"Endangered Whales\" on June 4th, 2018 {{!}} openparliament.ca|website=openparliament.ca|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nOn February 26, 2016, Erskine-Smith introduced Bill C-246, the Modernizing Animal Protections Act,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/10/06/nathaniel-erskine-smith-animal-cruelty-bill-c-246_n_12371614.html|title=Liberal MP's Animal Cruelty Bill Defeated|date=2016-10-06|website=HuffPost Canada|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> to ban the import of shark fins and make Canada's animal cruelty laws tougher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/09/09/beacheseast-york-mp-is-a-different-political-animal-delacourt.html|title=Beaches\u2014East York MP is a different political animal: Delacourt|date=2016-09-09|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The bill won support from EndCruelty, a coalition of Canadians who support stronger animal protection laws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://endcruelty.ca/|title=End Animal Cruelty \u2013 Support Bill C-246|website=EndCruelty.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Due to concerns from animal use lobbyists, the bill was defeated 198 to 84 at second reading. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/10/06/nathaniel-erskine-smith-animal-cruelty-bill-c-246_n_12371614.html|title=Liberal MP's Animal Cruelty Bill Defeated|date=2016-10-06|website=HuffPost Canada|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Two years later, a government bill addressing similar concerns was tabled by Justice Minister Jody Wilson-Raybould. She acknowledged Erskine-Smith\u2019s efforts as a precursor to the government\u2019s legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/politics/feds-to-ban-all-forms-of-bestiality-crack-down-on-animal-fighting-1.4139552|title=Feds to ban all forms of bestiality, crack down on animal fighting|date=2018-10-18|website=CTVNews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The defeat of Erskine-Smith\u2019s Bill C-246 led to the creation of the Liberal Animal Welfare Caucus in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2017/02/01/liberal-internal-caucus-to-focus-on-animal-welfare/|title=Liberal internal caucus to focus on animal welfare|last=Feb 1|first=Kelsey Johnson Published on|last2=2017 11:42am|date=2017-02-01|website=iPolitics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> On September 5, 2017, Erskine-Smith wrote a piece in Now Magazine addressing his veganism and the importance of a social change towards the treatment of animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/api/content/95e50ec6-927a-11e7-b25f-121bebc5777e/|title=Opinion: Why I\u2019m a vegan but don\u2019t consider myself an animal activist|last=Erskine-Smith|first=Nathaniel|date=2017-09-05|website=NOW Magazine|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n====== Animal Welfare Awards ======\nIn 2016, Erskine-Smith received the Humane Legislator Award from Animal Justice for his efforts to modernize Canada\u2019s federal animal protection laws with Bill C-246.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animaljustice.ca/blog/2016-pro-bono-humane-legislator-awards-recognize-outstanding-advocacy|title=2016 Pro Bono & Humane Legislator Awards Recognize Outstanding Advocates|date=2016-12-29|website=Animal Justice|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In 2017, Erskine-Smith received the Fur-Bearers\u2019 Clements award for his dedication to improving the lives of animals with Bill C-246.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/FURfree/posts/10154857911851269|title=The Fur-Bearers|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefurbearers.com/blog/episode-401-nathaniels-message-hope|title=EPISODE 401: NATHANIEL'S MESSAGE OF HOPE|last=|first=|date=2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2019, Erskine-Smith was awarded the Toronto Vegetarian Association Lisa Grill Compassion for Animals Award for his compassion and commitment toward animals. He was also recognized by Humane Canada for his dedication to ending animal abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/beynate/posts/2606045602847950|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/beynate/posts/2563478323771345|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Climate Action and Bill C-454 ====\nIn October 2018, Erskine-Smith called an emergency debate on climate change in Parliament in response to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change\u2019s special report on global warming. He requested action to be taken by the government and Canadians to ensure that Canada can reduce its emissions and reach the targeted goals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/10/16/trudeau-government-urged-to-step-up-climate-action-in-emergency-debate_a_23562480/|title=Trudeau Government Urged To Step Up Climate Action In Emergency Debate|date=2018-10-16|website=HuffPost Canada|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> On June 5, 2019, Erskine-Smith introduced Bill C-454, the Net-Zero Greenhouse Gas Emissions Act, to require the Government of Canada to reduce GHG emissions to net zero by 2050.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parl.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/bill/C-454/first-reading|title=Private Member's Bill C-454 (42-1) - First Reading - Net-Zero Greenhouse Gas Emissions Act - Parliament of Canada|website=www.parl.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/politics/federal/2019/06/05/liberal-mp-proposes-net-zero-emissions-target-for-2050.html|title=Liberal MP proposes \u2018net zero\u2019 emissions target for 2050|date=2019-06-05|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==== Drug Policy Reform and Bill C-460 ====\nErskine-Smith believes that the war on drugs has been a failure. He has been a vocal supporter of cannabis legalization and regulation, and has called for a new approach to treat drug use as a health issue. In February 2016, Erskine-Smith represented the Canadian government's pro-marijuana legalization views to a joint United Nations/Inter-Parliamentary Union conference reviewing how different countries were dealing with illegal drugs. He partnered with Mexican Senator Laura Rojas to argue that countries should seek alternatives to incarceration in cases where individuals have drugs solely for personal use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2016/02/08/liberal-mp-brings-governments-pro-pot-stance-to-world-stage/|title=Liberal MP brings government's pro-pot stance to world stage|last=Feb 8|first=Kyle Duggan Published on|last2=2016 5:00am|date=2016-02-08|website=iPolitics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In early January 2017, Erskine-Smith published an op-ed in Vice News Canada calling for the decriminalization of all drug possession as a logical next step to the government\u2019s progressive drug policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/3kpgw9/im-a-member-of-trudeaus-liberals-and-i-think-the-government-should-decriminalize-all-drugs|title=I'm a member of Trudeau's Liberals and I think the government should decriminalize all drugs|last=Erskine-Smith|first=Nathaniel|date=2017-01-26|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In late January 2017, Erskine-Smith delivered a speech in the House of Commons in support of Bill C-37, to expand access to safe injection clinics across Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcommons.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/house/sitting-130/hansard#Int-9331689|title=Debates (Hansard) No. 130 - January 31, 2017 (42-1) - House of Commons of Canada|website=www.ourcommons.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In the first episode of the television series Political Blind Date in 2017, Erskine-Smith and Conservative MP Garnett Genuis discussed their differing perspectives on the legalization of marijuana in Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2017/11/04/political-blind-date-series-hopes-opposites-attract-or-at-least-get-along.html|title=Political Blind Date series hopes opposites attract, or at least get along|date=2017-11-04|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Erskine-Smith introduced a Liberal caucus policy resolution to address the opioid crisis through a public health approach, and it was adopted as the second overall priority by the grassroots Liberal membership at the Liberal Policy Convention in Halifax in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/sex-work-drugs-and-pharmacare-what-liberals-want-in-2019-platform-1.3892062|title=Sex work, drugs and pharmacare: What Liberals want in 2019 platform|date=2018-04-21|website=CTVNews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Bill C-460 ====\nTo ensure more people access treatment, Nate introduced a bill to remove criminal sanctions for low-level possession and to reduce the stigma associated with seeking treatment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/decriminalization-drugs-canada_ca_5d0f8751e4b0aa375f4e1b8c|title=Why A Liberal MP Tabled A Bill To Decriminalize Hard Drugs At The Worst Time|date=2019-06-23|website=HuffPost Canada|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In 2018, Erskine-Smith appeared on CBC\u2019s Power & Politics to speak about his disappointment in the Liberal government\u2019s signing of the United States\u2019 \u2018War on Drugs\u2019 document. He argued it brought the conversation about drugs away from a health issue, which ran counter to his push for drug decriminalization and domestic policy at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/apr/16/canada-liberal-party-considers-decriminalization-all-illicit-drugs|title=Canada's Liberal party considers decriminalization of all illicit drugs|date=2018-04-16|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/player/play/1332258371793|title=Canada endorsed U.S. 'war on drugs' document to appease U.S., Liberal MP says|last=|first=|date=2018|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Cannabis Record Expungement ====\nErskine-Smith seconded a bill introduced by NDP MP Murray Rankin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/liberals-urged-to-follow-u-s-jurisdictions-to-expunge-cannabis-records-1.4337743|title=Liberals urged to follow U.S. jurisdictions to expunge cannabis records|last=Kirkup|first=Kristy|date=2019-03-15|website=CTVNews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In March 2019, Erskine-Smith wrote an op-ed for NOW Magazine where he discussed his support for MP Rankin\u2019s bill, stating that only expungements would address the injustice of cannabis criminalization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/api/content/9cc61654-41dd-11e9-b0fa-120e7ad5cf50/|title=Pot pardons don't go far enough to address racial injustices, says Liberal MP|last=Erskine-Smith|first=Nathaniel|date=2019-03-12|website=NOW Magazine|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Privacy Work ====\nIn 2017, Erskine-Smith traveled to Washington <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/beynate/posts/1465898100196045|title=Nathaniel Erskine-Smith|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> with the Access to Information, Privacy and Ethics committee to attend a congressional hearing on the Equifax data breach, and met with Congressmen from the Digital Commerce subcommittee, with Facebook<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/facebookappCanada/|title=Facebook app|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> privacy experts, and with officials from the Federal Trade Commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/federaltradecommission/|title=Federal Trade Commission|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In May 2018, Erskine-Smith scrutinized Facebook <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/|title=Facebook - Log In or Sign Up|website=Facebook|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>officials at the Standing Committee on Access to Information, Privacy and Ethics <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcommons.ca/Committees/en/ETHI|title=ETHI - Home - House of Commons of Canada|website=www.ourcommons.ca|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> regarding the Cambridge Analytica scandal and the extent of privacy breaches for Canadians.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-what-is-cambridge-analytica-and-what-did-it-do-a-guide/|title=Cambridge Analytica, AggregateIQ and the Facebook scandal: A guide to who\u2019s accused of what|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In 2018, Erskine-Smith participated as the Canadian delegation in the U.K.\u2019s International Grand Committee on social media and disinformation. In total, 24 officials from 9 countries representing 447 million people participated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://business.financialpost.com/technology/remember-the-internet-of-the-90s-thats-what-our-outdated-privacy-rules-were-built-to-handle|title=Remember the internet of the \u201990s? That\u2019s what Canada\u2019s outdated data protection laws were meant to handle {{!}} Financial Post|last=Innovation|date=2018-12-11|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In June 2018, Erskine-Smith introduced Bill-C413, an Act to amend the Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act, to give new powers for the Privacy Commissioner to better protect our privacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2018/06/20/liberal-backbencher-tables-bill-to-give-privacy-commissioner-more-power/|title=Liberal backbencher tables bill to give privacy commissioner more power|last=Jun 20|first=Sarah Turnbull Published on|last2=2018 4:00pm|date=2018-06-20|website=iPolitics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In May 2019, Erskine-Smith participated in the Canadian delegation of the International Grand Committee <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/facebook-zuckerberg-cambridge-analytica-1.5127007|title=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/facebook-zuckerberg-cambridge-analytica-1.5127007|last=|first=|date=2019|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> to meet with representatives from Google, Facebook and Twitter, among others. The Silicon Valley representatives were asked to defend their companies' records on protecting users' data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/facebook-grand-committee-tuesday-1.5152436|title='Call their bluff': Shut down social media platforms, ex-Facebook adviser urges|last=|first=|date=2019|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In August 2019, Erskine-Smith wrote an op-ed for the Toronto Star expressing his desire for the right to be forgotten. He explained that in an increasingly connected, online world citizens should have the right to hide content published about them from search engines if the individual\u2019s privacy is being seriously violated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/contributors/thebigdebate/2019/08/27/do-people-have-the-right-to-be-forgotten-on-the-internet.html|title=Do people have the right to be forgotten on the internet?|date=2019-08-27|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Current Parliament (43rd Parliament, 2019-Present): ===\n\n==== Committee Work ====\nErskine-Smith is a member of the Standing Committee on Industry, Science and Technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourcommons.ca/Committees/en/INDU?parl=42&session=1|title=INDU - Home - House of Commons of Canada|website=www.ourcommons.ca|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==== 2020 Private Members Bills ====\nHe introduced two bills in February 2020.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.beachmetro.com/2020/03/11/beaches-east-york-mp-introduces-private-members-bill-to-emphasize-public-health-over-criminal-charges-in-controlled-drugs-act/|title=Beaches-East York MP introduces Private Members Bill to emphasize public health over criminal charges in controlled drugs act|date=2020-03-11|website=Beach Metro Community News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==== Bill C-235 ====\nThis bill would delete the drug possession offence from the Criminal Code.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Bill C-236 ====\nThis bill would provide diversion options to law enforcement, crown attorneys, and judges for drug possession cases.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nErskine-Smith was raised [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]], and is now [[Veganism|vegan]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/09/09/beacheseast-york-mp-is-a-different-political-animal-delacourt.html|title=Beaches\u2014East York MP is a different political animal: Delacourt|last=Delacourt|first=Susan|date=September 6, 2016|website=thestar.com|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=October 1, 2016}}</ref> He has [[Crohn's disease]].<ref>{{Cite podcast|last=Domise|first=Andray|title=Legal Weed is Bad for Poor People|website=Canadaland Commons|publisher=[[Canadaland]]|date=February 22, 2016|url=http://www.canadalandshow.com/podcast/legal-weed-bad-poor-people-0|access-date=August 30, 2016|time=19:42}}</ref>\n\nErskine-Smith married Amelia \"Amy\" Symington, a prominent Toronto vegan chef and [[nutritionist]], on her family farm in [[Camlachie, Ontario]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The two met in an undergraduate [[film studies]] course at Queen's University.<ref name=\"Kingston\">{{Cite news|last=MacAlpine|first=Ian|url=http://www.thewhig.com/2015/10/26/council-run-helps-fuel-new-mps-success|title=Council run helps fuel new MP\u2019s success|date=October 26, 2015|newspaper=[[Kingston Whig-Standard]]|access-date=August 30, 2016}}</ref> They have two sons together.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.beachmetro.com/2020/01/07/beaches-east-york-mp-nathaniel-erskine-smith-helps-deliver-baby-son-crawford/|title=Beaches-East York MP Nathaniel Erskine-Smith helps deliver baby son Crawford|date=January 7, 2020|work=Beach Metro Community News|access-date=March 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2019|Beaches\u2014East York|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|[[Nathaniel Erskine-Smith]]|32,168|57.2|+7.75|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Mae J. Nam|11,964|21.3|-9.52|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|Nadirah Nazeer|7,957|14.2|-2.23|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Sean Manners|3,295|5.9|+3.32|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|PPC|Deborah McKenzie|822|1.5|-|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|56,206|100.0 &nbsp;|| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|80,981}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Liberal|}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Canada]]<ref>{{cite web |title=List of confirmed candidates |url=https://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/lst&document=index&lang=e |website=Elections Canada |accessdate=4 October 2019}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Election Night Results- |url=https://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts.aspx?lang=e |website=[[Elections Canada]] |accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n{{end}}\n{{Canadian federal election, 2015/Beaches\u2014East York}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Canadian Parliament links|18483}}\n*{{official website|http://nathanielerskinesmith.liberal.ca/}}\n*[https://votenate.ca Campaign Website]\n\n{{Current Members of the Canadian House of Commons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erskine-Smith, Nathaniel}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Queen's University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "SamSam177", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nathaniel_Erskine-Smith"}
{"title_page": "G. Kay Green", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n'''George Kay Green''' (born 3 May 1877, living 1939) was a Scottish architect whose work after 1918 was mostly in southern England. \n\n==Life==\nBorn in May 1877<ref name=1939register>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/61596/tna_r39_0929_0929d_015 1939 National Registration Act register for 241 Richmond Road, Twickenham] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>, Green was educated at [[George Watson's College]], [[Edinburgh]],<ref name=Watson>''A memorial record of Watsonians who served in the great war 1914'' (George Watson's College, Edinburgh, 1920), p. 1063: \u201cGREEN George Kay 1, Walpole St, S.W.3 ... GREEN, GEORGE KAY 1877 ; entd. 1880 ; R.E. (C. of E.), Q.M.S. ; R.A.S.C., 2/Lt. 1917.\u201d</ref> and was active in business in Edinburgh from at least 1897,<ref>David Goold, [http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=201183 George Kay Green Architect Biography Report], in Dictionary of Scottish Architects - DSA at Scottisharchitects.org.uk, accessed 2016-05-06</ref> when he went into partnership there with William H. McLachlan,<ref>Goold, [http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=202605 William H. McLachlan]</ref> but no trace has come to light that Green had a formal training as an architect.<ref name=themodernhouse>[https://www.themodernhouse.com/directory-of-architects-and-designers/g-kay-green/ George Kay Green] at themodernhouse.com</ref> In 1899, he submitted designs for a new [[Society of Writers to Her Majesty's Signet#The Signet Library|Signet Library]].<ref>Goold,  [http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/building_full.php?id=206499 Signet Library] in Dictionary of Scottish Architects</ref> A drawing by Green of the [[National Archives of Scotland#The Laigh Hall|Laigh Hall]], Edinburgh, appeared in the 1902 volume of the journal ''Judicial Review''.<ref>Iain Gordon Brown ''Building for Books: The Architectural Evolution of the Advocates' Library 1689-1925'' (Aberdeen University Press, 1989), p. xvii</ref> Green was in Edinburgh in 1909, when he wrote from there to ''The Berwick Advertiser'' on the subject of farming in the Borders.<ref> \u201dAn Object Lesson\u201d in ''The Berwick Advertiser''  (Northumberland, England), Friday 24 September 1909, p. 2: \u201dAn Object Lesson: Mr George Kay Green, Edinburgh, writes:\u2014 As one who has had special opportunities of studying the character and life of our Border farm tenants...\u201c</ref>\n\nDuring the [[World War I|First World War]], he served as an officer in the [[Royal Engineers]] and the [[Royal Army Service Corps]]. In 1920, he was living at 1, Walpole St, London S.W.3.<ref name=Watson/>\n\nIn 1927, Green was a director of Peacehaven Estates Ltd, Peacehaven Hotel Company Ltd, Peacehaven Water Company Ltd, and Peacehaven Electric Light Company Ltd., which had an address at South Coast Road, [[Peacehaven]], Sussex.<ref>''The Directory of Directors for 1927'' (Thomas Skinner & Co, 1927), p. 625</ref> In 1928 the companies also had an office at 7, [[Pall Mall, London|Pall Mall]], [[Westminster]], and the directors were [[Henry Roper-Curzon, 18th Baron Teynham|Lord Teynham]] (Chairman), C. W. Neville (Managing Director), and Green.<ref>''Garcke's Manual of Electricity Supply, Volume 32 (Electrical Press Limited, 1928), p. 752</ref> Peacehaven was a large self-build development described in 1940 as \"a holiday resort or bungalow-town... founded at the end of the War of 1914\u201318. It lies at the edge of the cliffs, its plan being a grid of unmade roads\".<ref>'Parishes: Piddinghoe', in L. F. Salzman, ed., ''A History of the County of Sussex: Volume 7, the Rape of Lewes'' (London, 1940), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/sussex/vol7/pp66-69 pp. 66-69] at British History Online, accessed 14 January 2018</ref>\n\nIn London, Green began to specialize in designing large apartment blocks. He was the architect of [[Sloane Avenue Mansions]], an 11-storey Art Deco residential building in [[Chelsea, London]], built between 1931 and 1933.<ref name=\"emporissloaneavenuemansions\">{{cite web|title=Sloane Avenue Mansions|url=http://www.emporis.com/buildings/1239386/sloane-avenue-mansions-london-united-kingdom|website=[[Emporis]]|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"concrete\">{{cite book|title=Concrete and Constructional Engineering|date=1934|publisher=Concrete Publications|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0PHNAAAAMAAJ&q=%22sloane+avenue+Mansions%22&dq=%22sloane+avenue+Mansions%22|volume=29}}</ref><ref name=\"manchesterhistory\">{{cite web|title=Sloane Avenue Mansions, London|url=http://manchesterhistory.net/architecture/1930/sloanemansions.html|website=manchesterhistory|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> Other such buildings he designed include [[Nell Gwynn House]] in Sloane Avenue, [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]], which was finished in 1937,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://londondecoflats.co.uk/estates/nell-gwynn-house/ |title=Nell Gwynn House |publisher=London Deco Flats |date= |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> and Du Cane Court, Balham High Road, [[Balham]], an early example of an apartment block with revolving doors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architecture.com/image-library/RIBApix/image-information/poster/du-cane-court-balham-high-road-balham-london-the-foyer-with-revolving-doors/posterid/RIBA24625.html |title=Du Cane Court, Balham High Road, Balham, London: the foyer with revolving doors &#124; RIBA |website=Architecture.com |date= |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> When Du Cane Court was completed in 1934, it was the largest block of flats in Great Britain.<ref>''Proceedings of the Huguenot Society of Great Britain and Ireland'', Volume 27 (Huguenot Society, 1998), p. 142</ref>\n\n==Private life==\nIn May 1930, at [[Brighton]], Green married Edna Kathleen Hiscock,<ref>\u201dMarriages\u201d in ''West Sussex Gazette'', Thursday 08 May 1930, p. 12; \u201dGreen George K & Hiscock Edna K\u201d in Index to Register of Marriages for Brighton, 1930, referring to register vol. 2b, p. 607; [https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1623/31280_198347-00541 Register entry] at St Stephen\u2019s, Hounslow, at ancestry.co.uk,  {{subscription}}</ref> the 27-year-old daughter of a builder, Herbert Woodbridge Hiscock, and his wife Eleanor.<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1558/31280_198341-00473 Baptism at Hounslow in 1903] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> In 1935, they were living at 241, Richmond Road, Twickenham, and the next year at 1, Wimpole Street, Chelsea.<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1795/40020_218994-00494 electoral register 1935] and [https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1795/40020_190534-00128 1936] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> In September 1936, they announced the birth of a son, Charles.<ref>\u201cBirths\u201d in \n[[The Scotsman]] (Midlothian, Scotland), 16 September 1936, p. 20: \u201cAt 1 Walpole Street, Chelsea London S.W. 5, on September 12th, 1936, to Edna, wife of G. Kay Green, a son\u201d; \u201cGREEN Charles E K / Hiscock\u201d in Index to Register of Births for Chelsea, 1936, referring to vol. 1a, p. 432</ref> The Post Office Directory for 1938 has Green listed at 8, Orange Street, [[Haymarket, London|Haymarket]], Westminster W.C.2.<ref>\u201cArchitects\u201d,''Post Office London Private Residents Directory for 1938'', p. 2660</ref> In October 1939, the family of three was back in Twickenham.<ref name=1939register/>\n\nWhen Green\u2019s widow died in 1993, her death was registered as Edna Kathleen Green or Kay-Green.<ref>\u201cGreen or Kay-Green, Edna Kathleen, Birth 04/12/1902, Death 04/1993, Northern Surrey\u201d in Index to Register of Deaths for Northern Surrey, 1936</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.themodernhouse.com/directory-of-architects-and-designers/g-kay-green/ George Kay Green] at themodernhouse.com\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Green, George Kay}}\n[[Category:Scottish architects]]\n[[Category:People educated at George Watson's College]]\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1940s deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n'''George Kay Green''' (born 3 May 1877, living 1939) was a Scottish architect whose work after 1918 was mostly in southern England. \n\n==Life==\nBorn in May 1877<ref name=1939register>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/61596/tna_r39_0929_0929d_015 1939 National Registration Act register for 241 Richmond Road, Twickenham] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>, Green was educated at [[George Watson's College]], [[Edinburgh]],<ref name=Watson>''A memorial record of Watsonians who served in the great war 1914'' (George Watson's College, Edinburgh, 1920), p. 1063: \u201cGREEN George Kay 1, Walpole St, S.W.3 ... GREEN, GEORGE KAY 1877 ; entd. 1880 ; R.E. (C. of E.), Q.M.S. ; R.A.S.C., 2/Lt. 1917.\u201d</ref> and was active in business in Edinburgh from at least 1897,<ref>David Goold, [http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=201183 George Kay Green Architect Biography Report], in Dictionary of Scottish Architects - DSA at Scottisharchitects.org.uk, accessed 2016-05-06</ref> when he went into partnership there with William H. McLachlan,<ref>Goold, [http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=202605 William H. McLachlan]</ref> but no trace has come to light that Green had a formal training as an architect.<ref name=themodernhouse>[https://www.themodernhouse.com/directory-of-architects-and-designers/g-kay-green/ George Kay Green] at themodernhouse.com</ref> In 1899, he submitted designs for a new [[Society of Writers to Her Majesty's Signet#The Signet Library|Signet Library]].<ref>Goold,  [http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/building_full.php?id=206499 Signet Library] in Dictionary of Scottish Architects</ref> A drawing by Green of the [[National Archives of Scotland#The Laigh Hall|Laigh Hall]], Edinburgh, appeared in the 1902 volume of the journal ''Judicial Review''.<ref>Iain Gordon Brown ''Building for Books: The Architectural Evolution of the Advocates' Library 1689-1925'' (Aberdeen University Press, 1989), p. xvii</ref> Green was in Edinburgh in 1909, when he wrote from there to ''The Berwick Advertiser'' on the subject of farming in the Borders.<ref> \u201dAn Object Lesson\u201d in ''The Berwick Advertiser''  (Northumberland, England), Friday 24 September 1909, p. 2: \u201dAn Object Lesson: Mr George Kay Green, Edinburgh, writes:\u2014 As one who has had special opportunities of studying the character and life of our Border farm tenants...\u201c</ref>\n\nDuring the [[World War I|First World War]], he served as an officer in the [[Royal Engineers]] and the [[Royal Army Service Corps]]. In 1920, he was living at 1, Walpole St, London S.W.3.<ref name=Watson/>\n\nIn 1927, he was a director of Peacehaven Estates Ltd, Peacehaven Hotel Company Ltd, Peacehaven Water Company Ltd, and Peacehaven Electric Light Company Ltd., which had an address at South Coast Road, [[Peacehaven]], Sussex.<ref>''The Directory of Directors for 1927'' (Thomas Skinner & Co, 1927), p. 625</ref> In 1928 the companies also had an office at 7, [[Pall Mall, London|Pall Mall]], [[Westminster]], and the directors were [[Henry Roper-Curzon, 18th Baron Teynham|Lord Teynham]] (Chairman), C. W. Neville (Managing Director), and Green.<ref>''Garcke's Manual of Electricity Supply, Volume 32 (Electrical Press Limited, 1928), p. 752</ref> Peacehaven was a large self-build development described in 1940 as \"a holiday resort or bungalow-town... founded at the end of the War of 1914\u201318. It lies at the edge of the cliffs, its plan being a grid of unmade roads\".<ref>'Parishes: Piddinghoe', in L. F. Salzman, ed., ''A History of the County of Sussex: Volume 7, the Rape of Lewes'' (London, 1940), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/sussex/vol7/pp66-69 pp. 66-69] at British History Online, accessed 14 January 2018</ref>\n\nIn London, Green began to specialize in designing large apartment blocks. He was the architect of [[Sloane Avenue Mansions]], an 11-storey Art Deco residential building in [[Chelsea, London]], built between 1931 and 1933.<ref name=\"emporissloaneavenuemansions\">{{cite web|title=Sloane Avenue Mansions|url=http://www.emporis.com/buildings/1239386/sloane-avenue-mansions-london-united-kingdom|website=[[Emporis]]|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"concrete\">{{cite book|title=Concrete and Constructional Engineering|date=1934|publisher=Concrete Publications|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0PHNAAAAMAAJ&q=%22sloane+avenue+Mansions%22&dq=%22sloane+avenue+Mansions%22|volume=29}}</ref><ref name=\"manchesterhistory\">{{cite web|title=Sloane Avenue Mansions, London|url=http://manchesterhistory.net/architecture/1930/sloanemansions.html|website=manchesterhistory|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> Other such buildings he designed include [[Nell Gwynn House]] in Sloane Avenue, [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]], which was finished in 1937,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://londondecoflats.co.uk/estates/nell-gwynn-house/ |title=Nell Gwynn House |publisher=London Deco Flats |date= |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> and Du Cane Court, Balham High Road, [[Balham]], an early example of an apartment block with revolving doors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architecture.com/image-library/RIBApix/image-information/poster/du-cane-court-balham-high-road-balham-london-the-foyer-with-revolving-doors/posterid/RIBA24625.html |title=Du Cane Court, Balham High Road, Balham, London: the foyer with revolving doors &#124; RIBA |website=Architecture.com |date= |accessdate=2016-05-06}}</ref> When Du Cane Court was completed in 1934, it was the largest block of flats in Great Britain.<ref>''Proceedings of the Huguenot Society of Great Britain and Ireland'', Volume 27 (Huguenot Society, 1998), p. 142</ref>\n\n==Private life==\nIn May 1930, at [[Brighton]], Green married Edna Kathleen Hiscock,<ref>\u201dMarriages\u201d in ''West Sussex Gazette'', Thursday 08 May 1930, p. 12; \u201dGreen George K & Hiscock Edna K\u201d in Index to Register of Marriages for Brighton, 1930, referring to register vol. 2b, p. 607; [https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1623/31280_198347-00541 Register entry] at St Stephen\u2019s, Hounslow, at ancestry.co.uk,  {{subscription}}</ref> the 27-year-old daughter of a builder, Herbert Woodbridge Hiscock, and his wife Eleanor.<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1558/31280_198341-00473 Baptism at Hounslow in 1903] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> In 1935, they were living at 241, Richmond Road, Twickenham, and the next year at 1, Wimpole Street, Chelsea.<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1795/40020_218994-00494 electoral register 1935] and [https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/1795/40020_190534-00128 1936] at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> In September 1936, they announced the birth of a son, Charles.<ref>\u201cBirths\u201d in \n[[The Scotsman]] (Midlothian, Scotland), 16 September 1936, p. 20: \u201cAt 1 Walpole Street, Chelsea London S.W. 5, on September 12th, 1936, to Edna, wife of G. Kay Green, a son\u201d; \u201cGREEN Charles E K / Hiscock\u201d in Index to Register of Births for Chelsea, 1936, referring to vol. 1a, p. 432</ref> The Post Office Directory for 1938 has Green listed at 8, Orange Street, [[Haymarket, London|Haymarket]], Westminster W.C.2.<ref>\u201cArchitects\u201d,''Post Office London Private Residents Directory for 1938'', p. 2660</ref> In October 1939, the family of three was back in Twickenham.<ref name=1939register/>\n\nWhen Green\u2019s widow died in 1993, her death was registered as Edna Kathleen Green or Kay-Green.<ref>\u201cGreen or Kay-Green, Edna Kathleen, Birth 04/12/1902, Death 04/1993, Northern Surrey\u201d in Index to Register of Deaths for Northern Surrey, 1936</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.themodernhouse.com/directory-of-architects-and-designers/g-kay-green/ George Kay Green] at themodernhouse.com\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Green, George Kay}}\n[[Category:Scottish architects]]\n[[Category:People educated at George Watson's College]]\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1940s deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Moonraker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G._Kay_Green"}
